		<li class="alt" id="comment-606">
			<div class="comment"><span class="commentauthor">Karin's Mom says:</span>
						<br />

			<small><a href="#comments-606" title="">February 11th, 2009 at 8:41 pm</a> </small></div>

			<div class="comment"><p>Tim,<br />
Why do you use unsalted butter in most recipes? Is using unsalted butter a health choice or does unsalted butter have a cooking purpose?</p>
</div>

		</li>
	
	
		<li id="comment-608">
			<div class="comment"><span class="commentauthor"><span style=""><a href='http://admin' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Tim</a></span> says:</span>
						<br />

			<small><a href="#comments-608" title="">February 11th, 2009 at 9:28 pm</a> </small></div>

			<div class="comment"><div style="font-weight: bold;">
<p>Hey Karin&#8217;s Mom: Recipes call for unsalted butter as a way of controlling salt content. Since salted butters all contain different amounts of salt it would be impossible to predict final results. Recipes would not be as accurately duplicated. By using unsalted butter and adding salt yourself you are more likely to replicate what the recipe&#8217;s creator had in mind. You can still use salted butter for a recipe like this, you would just reduce the additional salt you are adding to the recipe. In this recipe I would probably just add a pinch of salt. Hope that helps!</p>
</div>
</div>

		</li>
	
	
