			<div class="comment"><span class="commentauthor">Renee says:</span>
						<br />

			<small><a href="#comments-5173" title="">July 18th, 2010 at 3:02 pm</a> </small></div>

			<div class="comment"><p>All of this recent paranoia about the need for EXACT measurements for baking has reminded me that our grandmothers didn&#8217;t use consistent measurements at all, and they were the ones after whose baking we tend to lust!  We use &#8220;cups&#8221;, &#8220;teaspoons&#8221;, etc. because prior to the middle of the 20th century, most bakers used actual teacups, spoons, etc. to measure their ingredients, and you need to understand that not all teacups, or spoons, were the same size.</p>
</div>

